    "encrypted": "false",
    "title": "Skill Building",
    "long_instructions": "## Using Formulas\r\n\r\n#### When trying to analyze our data, finding the sum, count, and average of a range elements can help us quickly understand the data.\r\n\r\n#### Need a new copy of the dataset? <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1lg67vrIpnXaCe7P-XjqLmf6x91UcEvB-Ikw_rpqJDG8/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Google Sheets Link</a>\r\n\r\n## Sum\r\n\r\n#### **1. How many inversions do stand up coasters have in total?**\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/59c9b8a356ff4e56ec8c802ba5718b37-image-1684269154206.png\" alt=\"A clipboard with the words TO DO on it. This icon is used to signal an action item for participants.\" width=\"35px\" style=\"border-radius:10px; float:left; margin: 0px 10px 0px 0px;\">\r\n\r\n###**Do This:**\r\n\r\n>#### Try solving it both ways:\r\n>#### 1. Add a `SUM` formula that specifies the range.\r\n>#### 2. Highlight the specified cells and use the Sum tally at the bottom right.\r\n\r\n#### *Hint: Consider sorting or filtering the dataset first to make it easier to calculate the sum.*\r\n\r\n:::details [🔎**Show Me How**]\r\n#### 1. Use `=SUM` to call the sum function\r\n#### 2. Specify the range by typing it in. EX: `=SUM(N92:N105)`\r\n#### 3. Press Enter to escape out of the cell and run your formula\r\n:::\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n## COUNTIF\r\n\r\n#### **2. How many roller coasters were built before 1950?**\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/59c9b8a356ff4e56ec8c802ba5718b37-image-1684269154206.png\" alt=\"A clipboard with the words TO DO on it. This icon is used to signal an action item for participants.\" width=\"35px\" style=\"border-radius:10px; float:left; margin: 0px 10px 0px 0px;\">\r\n\r\n### **Do This:**\r\n\r\n>#### 1. Use the `COUNTIF` formula to specify the range.\r\n>#### 2. Then specify the criteria to determine which entries to count.\r\n\r\n:::details [🔎**Show Me How**]\r\n#### 1. Remember to use the formula `=COUNTIF(range, criteria)`\r\n#### 2. First, specify the range: `=COUNTIF(D2:D158, criteria)`\r\n#### 3. Then, specific the criteria of greater than 60 mph: `=COUNTIF(D2:D158, \">60\")`\r\n#### 4. Press Enter to escape out of the cell and run your formula\r\n:::\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n##Average\r\n\r\n#### **3. What is the average duration of roller coasters in California?**\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://images.code.org/59c9b8a356ff4e56ec8c802ba5718b37-image-1684269154206.png\" alt=\"A clipboard with the words TO DO on it. This icon is used to signal an action item for participants.\" width=\"35px\" style=\"border-radius:10px; float:left; margin: 0px 10px 0px 0px;\">\r\n\r\n### **Do This:**\r\n\r\n>#### Try solving it both ways:\r\n>#### 1. Add an `AVERAGE` formula that specifies the range.\r\n>#### 2. Highlight the specified cells and use the Average tally at the bottom right.\r\n\r\n#### *Hint: Consider sorting or filtering the dataset first to make it easier to calculate the average.*\r\n\r\n:::details [🔎**Show Me How**]\r\n#### 1. Use `=AVERAGE` to call the sum function\r\n#### 2. Specify the range by typing it in `=AVERAGE(G2:G158)`\r\n#### 3. Press Enter to escape out of the cell and run your formula\r\n:::\r\n\r\n<br>",
    "teacher_markdown": "![](https://images.code.org/9a204b20b525e4f5272d2f49d9207cfd-image-1721836085919.png)\r\n\r\nExample student response:\r\n- California and Pennsylvania have the most roller coasters at 18.\r\n\r\nOther questions students may wonder about and investigate include:\r\n- What is the average age of roller coasters in states with the most versus the least roller coasters? Or Do states with more roller coasters have a wider variety of coaster types? Or How does the intensity of roller coasters (as measured by speed, height, or inversions) compare across states with different numbers of coasters?\r\n- Whatever questions students investigate, they should be relevant to the dataset and its attributes. The insights they gain from any new graphs created should be directly related to the questions posed and supported by the data analysis conducted. They should be clear, concise, and logically derived from the data. Teachers should value insights that show unique thinking or new connections.\r\n",
